    <!--Fifth Grade -->
    <subsection><title>Fifth Grade</title>
    <assemblage>
            <title>Context 1: Solar energy and soils, elements needed to grow our food </title>
            <p>In this context, students will relate to how Indigenous peoples connect to the sun and use solar energy, including through renewable energy technology like photovoltaics. Students can relate science standards to the need for healthy soils for farming. </p> 
       </assemblage> 
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Support an argument that differences in the apparent brightness of the sun compared to other stars is due to their relative distances from the Earth.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class or take home exercise:</em>Introduce students to photovoltaics by discussing how some Native communities in the Southwest rely on solar energy technology to provide electricity in their homes. Show students the Native Renewables website (<url href="https://www.nativerenewables.org/" />). Download and pass out the zine created by Native Renewables that explains photovoltaics (<url href="https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5f491be9a82eed6a01fd24ac/t/6018a18e281db443ae79bb0e/1612226961043/Solar%2BMinizine%2Bv14.pdf" />). 
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em>What are ways you use electricity in your homes? What happens when your home doesn’t have electricity? Why do photovoltaics only work during the day? Can photovoltaics work at night using light from other stars? 
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS1-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Represent data in graphical displays to reveal patterns of daily changes in length and direction of shadows, day and night, and the seasonal appearance of some stars in the night sky.
        </p>
        <p><em>Take home exercise:</em> Introduce students to passive solar energy by handing out this handout on passive solar home design in NM (<url href="https://www.nmsolar.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Passive-Solar-Design.pdf" />). 
        </p>
        <p>Ask students to walk around their home, village, and neighborhoods to identify how some homes make use of passive solar energy.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model using an example to describe ways the geosphere, biosphere, hydrosphere, and/or
atmosphere interacts.
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em> How do you interact with each of the spheres? What sphere is your home built on and the materials used for your home built on? What sphere does your food come from? How does the sun interact with each sphere?
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS2-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Describe and graph the amounts and percentages of water and fresh water in various reservoirs to provide
evidence about the distribution of water on Earth.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss with students how water is distributed in New Mexico. Refer to the FAQs about water page of the NM Bureau of Geology and Mineral Resources: <url href="https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/faq/water/home.html"/>). Relate to the global distribution of rainfall (<url href="https://www.climate-charts.com/World-Climate-Maps.html" />) and discuss how NM is in an arid climate and we get a lot of solar radiation that easily evaporates our rainfall. Thus, we have less surface water and rely more on groundwater compared to other areas in the world.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS3-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Obtain and combine information about ways individual communities use science ideas to protect the Earth’s resources and environment.
        </p>
        <p><em>Take home or in-class exercise:</em> Introduce students to the NM Tribal Resilience Action Network by showing this YouTube video that discusses how Pueblos and Tribes in NM are addressing climate change: <video youtube="eRwiJaz2n14"/>
        </p>
        <p>Also, refer to the Eight Northern Indian Pueblos, Inc.-Office of Environmental Technical Assistance website (<url href="http://enipc-oeta.org/home.htm"/>) to discuss how Pueblos are addressing other environmental issues. </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-LS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Support an argument that plants get the materials they need for growth chiefly from air and water.
        </p>
        <p><em>Take home or in-class exercise:</em> Invite a Pueblo farmer to talk to students about Pueblo farming practices or ask students to talk to a family or community member about how the work they do in their fields to help their crops grow. </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-LS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model to describe the movement of matter among plants, animals, decomposers, and the
environment.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Introduce students to the role of soil in decomposing plant and animal matter and other environmental functions by showing this YouTube video about soil health in NM: <url href="https://www.nmhealthysoil.org/2021/06/14/soil-care-is-climate-repair/"/>. </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model to describe that matter is made of particles too small to be seen.
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em> What are photons? How are photons from the Sun used to generate electricity?</p>
        <p> <em>External resource:</em> How a PV Cell works: <url href="https://www.solarschools.net/knowledge-bank/renewable-energy/solar/how-a-pv-cell-works" />
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Measure and graph quantities to provide evidence that regardless of the type of change that occurs when
heating, cooling, or mixing substances, the total weight of matter is conserved.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Materials needed: scale or balance, jars with lids, thermometer, marker, soil collected from different natural local locations.</p>
<p>
Fill a jar halfway full with water and close tightly with a lid. Stick a thermometer in the water and weigh the jar. Record the weight and the temperature. Then, stick the jar outside to be warmed by the sun. After several minutes, record the temperature and weight. </p>
<p>
Next, use the jar and water to conduct soil texture activity (<url href="https://www.soils4kids.org/files/s4k/soil-texture-experiment.pdf"/>). Tell students where soils were collected from so they can figure out the soil texture in those locations. </p>
<p>
Refer to the “Background Agricultural Connections” portion of this website (<url href="https://agclassroom.org/matrix/lesson/print/365/"/>)
 to talk to students about the importance of knowing soil texture for farming. Next, mix two different types of soil samples and redo the soil texture analysis.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-3</title>
        <p>
          Description: Make observations and measurements to identify materials based on their properties.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Materials needed: scale or balance, jars with lids, thermometer, marker, soil collected from different natural local locations.</p>
<p>
Fill a jar halfway full with water and close tightly with a lid. Stick a thermometer in the water and weigh the jar. Record the weight and the temperature. Then, stick the jar outside to be warmed by the sun. After several minutes, record the temperature and weight. </p>
<p>
Next, use the jar and water to conduct soil texture activity (<url href="https://www.soils4kids.org/files/s4k/soil-texture-experiment.pdf"/>). Tell students where soils were collected from so they can figure out the soil texture in those locations. </p>
<p>
Refer to the “Background Agricultural Connections” portion of this website (<url href="https://agclassroom.org/matrix/lesson/print/365/"/>)
 to talk to students about the importance of knowing soil texture for farming. Next, mix two different types of soil samples and redo the soil texture analysis.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-4</title>
        <p>
          Description: Conduct an investigation to determine whether the mixing of two or more substances results in new
substances.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Materials needed: scale or balance, jars with lids, thermometer, marker, soil collected from different natural local locations.</p>
<p>
Fill a jar halfway full with water and close tightly with a lid. Stick a thermometer in the water and weigh the jar. Record the weight and the temperature. Then, stick the jar outside to be warmed by the sun. After several minutes, record the temperature and weight. </p>
<p>
Next, use the jar and water to conduct soil texture activity (<url href="https://www.soils4kids.org/files/s4k/soil-texture-experiment.pdf"/>). Tell students where soils were collected from so they can figure out the soil texture in those locations. </p>
<p>
Refer to the “Background Agricultural Connections” portion of this website (<url href="https://agclassroom.org/matrix/lesson/print/365/"/>)
 to talk to students about the importance of knowing soil texture for farming. Next, mix two different types of soil samples and redo the soil texture analysis.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Support an argument that the gravitational force exerted by Earth on objects is directed down.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Conduct this activity on soil infiltration (<url href="https://sndl.ucmerced.edu/files/MHWG/Field/Southern_Sierra_CZO_KREW/Education_and_Outreach/Activities/Activity3_SoilInfiltrationandTexture.pdf"/>)</p>
<p>
Relate this activity to how when water is applied to crop fields the water moves into the soil due to gravity.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS3-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Use models to describe that energy in animals’ food (used for body repair, growth, motion, and to maintain
body warmth) was once energy from the sun.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Relate concepts to farming and gardening practices used to grow food for Pueblo people. Refer to the “Pueblo Farming Methods for your Resilient Garden” webpage and videos embedded on the webpage (<url href="https://thegrownetwork.com/pueblo-farming-methods/"/>).
        </p>
      </example>
    </subsection>
